player.seasonOutlook: Some fantasy managers were likely disappointed with Hellebuyck's play last season, but a closer look at the numbers tells us that all his important statistics (2.58 GAA, .916 save percentage, four shutouts) were roughly right in line with his 2019-20 Vezina Trophy-winning campaign. He also played very well (2.23 GAA, .931 save percentage) in eight playoff starts. Hellebuyck isn't on the level of Andrei Vasilevskiy, but he should be the next best option in goal for fantasy managers in drafts this fall. Hellebuyck, who turned 28 last May, should remain a top-tier goaltending option for several more seasons.

Crosby has averaged more than a point per game every season during his storied career, and the 2020-21 campaign (24 goals, 62 points in 55 games) was no exception. The most positive development of all, though, was that Crosby played in all but one of Pittsburgh's 56 regular-season games. There's some injury risk here given the fact Sid is entering his age-34 campaign, but he's a clear-cut late first-rounder as long as his body holds up. Crosby gets an extra bump in leagues that value faceoffs given the fact he's won at least 53 percent of his draws four years running.

In terms of hits and shots on goal, there is an argument to be made that Tkachuk is one the most valuable players in the league from a fantasy standpoint. The soon-to-be 22-year-old is fresh off a season featuring 17 goals, 36 points, 220 shots, 10 power-play points and 248 hits in just 56 games. If that's not enough, there is additional hope for improvement in the goal department in 2021-22 given that Tkachuk's shooting percentage a season ago was 7.7 percent -- the lowest of his three-year career. The Senators remain a rebuilding team, and all this production will likely come with a terrible plus-minus rating attached, but Tkachuk brings a skill set to the fantasy table that few others can match.

A perfect fit for Carolina's uptempo offense, Hamilton finished tied for seventh in scoring among defensemen (10 goals, 42 points in 55 games) last season. 19 of those points came with the man advantage, and Hamilton finished with a plus-20 rating for good measure. He is also always among the league leaders in shots on goal among rearguards. It's an enticing all-around package for fantasy managers, but he'll likely be hard-pressed to match that production with his new team in New Jersey. Hamilton will still be worthy of an early-round selection, but his fantasy appeal isn't likely to increase, so poolies should be mindful of that before rolling with the 28-year-old.

After four straight seasons between 39 and 45 points in Carolina, Lindholm took his game to a different level upon being traded to Calgary. In three campaigns with the Flames, the 26-year-old Swede has totaled 75 goals and 179 points in 207 games (a 30-goal, 71-point 82-game pace). Lindholm's pedestrian shot totals put a slight damper on his value, but he makes up for the lack of volume with good efficiency, and it's hard to argue with his recent results.

Hyman missed Toronto's final 11 regular-season games with a knee injury and was basically invisible (one goal) in the Leafs' seven-game first-round playoff loss to Montreal. However, that didn't stop the Oilers from handing him a seven-year, $38.5 million contract as an unrestricted free agent this summer. It might seem like a bit of an overpayment on the surface, but Hyman has tallied at least 15 goals in each of the last four seasons and has a proven track record playing alongside superstars. He figures to flank Connor McDavid in Edmonton, and if he doesn't, he'll be alongside another stud in Leon Draisaitl. That, combined with an expected increased role on the power play, make Hyman a potentially sneaky value pick this fall.

Svechnikov actually had a disappointing 2020-21 fantasy campaign relative to the enormous expectations placed upon him entering the year. He managed just 15 goals in 55 games, though his shots on goal (147), power-play production (17 points) and hits (114) were perfectly reasonable. Svechnikov's talent isn't in doubt and he won't turn 22 until late March, but the Hurricanes are one of the deepest teams in the NHL and a club that tends to spread the wealth offensively. The 2018 No. 2 overall selection has a high fantasy floor heading into his fourth season, but managers probably shouldn't be banking on a breakout that hasn't come to fruition yet.

Demko began last season expected to split time with veteran Braden Holtby, but by the time it was done, the youngster saw action in 35 of Vancouver's 56 games. His numbers (16-18-1, 2.85 GAA, .916 save percentage) were fair given how many injuries the Canucks dealt with over the course of the year. Vancouver clearly believes in Demko, as it signed him to a five-year, $25 million contract in March. They brought in a capable backup in Jaroslav Halak on a one-year deal, but Halak is 36 and shouldn't seriously threaten Demko's playing time. Demko has significant fantasy upside if the Canucks can rebound as a team this season.

Eriksson Ek managed just 24 goals in 210 games over the course of his first four NHL seasons, but he upped that total to 19 in 56 games during the shortened 2020-21 campaign. Impressed with what they saw, the Wild handed Eriksson Ek an eight-year, $42 million contract extension. The Swede is responsible defensively and brings more things to the table than just his goal-scoring, but one can't help but think Erikkson Ek's offensive breakout was driven by an unsustainable 16.0 shooting percentage. His highest number the prior three years was just 7.8 percent. The upside here isn't all that great, making Eriksson Ek nothing more than a late-round fantasy play in most scenarios.

A disappointment since being drafted No. 4 overall by the Flames in 2014, Bennett found new life following an April trade to the Panthers. He posted six goals and 15 points in 10 games with his new club and was rewarded with a fresh four-year, $17.7 million contract this summer. It's a contract that will obviously be a bargain if Bennett continues scoring at the same rate we saw late last year, but it's also a major risk given how ineffective he's been for the majority of his career. Fantasy managers would be wise to stay away until Bennett puts forth another strong campaign.

Larkin recorded career lows across the board with nine goals and 23 points over 44 games last season before his campaign was cut short by a neck injury. The injury isn't supposed to linger into the upcoming season, but Larkin has plenty of other red flags given his rapid decline since posting career highs in goals (32) and points (73) in 2018-19. Detroit's 25-year-old captain has just 28 goals, 76 points and a minus-35 rating in 115 subsequent appearances. His team is expected to languish near the bottom of the standings again, so Larkin's rating woes will likely continue, but his offense should trend back up if he's healthy.

Scheifele's controversial suspension in the playoffs overshadowed the latest productive regular season from Winnipeg's top-line center. With 21 goals and 63 points in 56 games, Scheifele reached or exceeded a point-per-game pace for the fifth consecutive campaign. He'll sit out the first game of the season as he completes his suspension, but Scheifele should get back to being one of the league's top scorers after that, as he's still in the middle of his prime at age 28.

Kane has a high floor and the ability to produce monstrous offensive seasons every now and again. He has performed at a point-per-game pace or better for eight of the last nine seasons, including a pair of campaigns with at least 106 points. The 32-year-old winger's aging gracefully, and Kane's excellent puck-handling skills make him especially dangerous with the extra man, as evidenced by his current string of eight consecutive seasons with at least 22 power-play points. His goal total dropped below 20 for the first time last season due to a career-worst 7.9 shooting percentage, but the career 11.9 percent shooter's in good position to bounce back with some better puck luck, especially with Chicago having loaded up in the offseason for another run with its veteran core.

Few players in the NHL are as reliable as Nelson. He's finished each of the last seven seasons with at least 18 goals while cracking the 40-point mark five times during that span. Nelson sees about 18 minutes of average ice time, including a couple minutes with the man advantage. No team in the league relies on structure and spreading the offense around more than the Islanders, so Nelson's fantasy upside is fairly limited, but there's some deep-league value here for fantasy managers looking for consistent late-round offensive production.

Despite reaching the 20-goal plateau (22) and finishing with 42 points over 56 games, Rust actually took a step back last season compared to his 56-points-in-55-games showing the year prior. Now 29, the Michigan native's roles on Pittsburgh's top line and No. 1 power-play unit -- with studs Sidney Crosby and Jake Guentzel -- appear secure, which should continue to be a boon to his fantasy stock. It's no fault of Rust's, but it's hard to tell how much of his success is tied to his linemates, but fantasy managers won't care as long as he's producing. Just be mindful of his 14-point production dip last year, especially given the fact he received just one second less of average power-play time (2:47) than the season prior.

Barzal is an excellent playmaker and an above-average NHL center, but he will probably never again be the guy that posted 85 points in his 2017-18 Calder Trophy-winning campaign. Barzal finished with 17 goals and 45 points in 55 games in 2020-21, which would amount to 25 goals and 69 points over a full 82-game schedule. Those types of numbers would appear to be reasonable targets moving forward. One of the biggest questions surrounds Barzal's linemates going forward. He spent the majority of last year with Jordan Eberle on his right side and a revolving door of guys on his left. Eberle was scooped by Seattle in the expansion draft, and the Islanders would be best served by a sniper to flank Barzal, maximizing the return on his playmaking abilities.

In terms of fantasy production, Doughty essentially turned into a one-dimensional power-play weapon last season. 17 of his 33 points came with the man advantage, meaning he managed just 16 non-power-play points in 56 regular-season games. That's simply not going to get the job done considering Doughty has posted no better than a minus-14 rating in each of the past three seasons. Doughty almost never misses a game and offers additional value in leagues that value hits and blocks, but he's trending downward at age 31 and appears unlikely to be a key cog for Los Angeles when its massive stable of prospects are finally ready to contribute at the NHL level.

He dealt with multiple injuries during the year, but Pacioretty was money for Vegas whenever he was in the lineup. He finished top-25 in the league in both goals (24) and points (51) despite missing eight regular-season games. He also missed Vegas' first six playoff contests. The goals may dip a bit next year considering Pacioretty's 13.8 shooting percentage (his highest since 2013-14) is due for regression, but his secure role with both the man advantage and on one of Golden Knights' scoring lines makes the Connecticut native one of the safest picks in fantasy hockey.
